LAYER 3: CEREBELLUM
the error corrector

observe 1_quantum.rana
observe 2_chemical.rana

the cerebellum contains more neurons than the rest of the brain combined
approximately 50 billion granule cells and 15 million Purkinje cells
it sits behind the brainstem cradled in the posterior cranial fossa
it receives a copy of every motor command the cortex issues
it compares what was intended with what actually happened
and it corrects the difference
every movement Fadriel has ever made was refined here

STRUCTURE cerebellar_cortex | surface | three layers
    molecular_layer | outermost | contains parallel fibers from granule cells and dendrites of Purkinje cells | the computational grid where input meets output
    purkinje_cell_layer | middle | single row of Purkinje cells | massive dendritic arbors extending into the molecular layer like flat trees | each Purkinje cell receives input from approximately 200000 parallel fibers and exactly 1 climbing fiber
    granular_layer | deepest | packed with granule cells the smallest neurons in the body | each granule cell sends a thin axon upward that bifurcates into two parallel fibers running perpendicular to Purkinje dendrites
STRUCTURE climbing_fibers | input from inferior olive | each climbing fiber wraps around a single Purkinje cell with hundreds of synaptic contacts | carries the ERROR signal | "what you predicted was WRONG"
STRUCTURE mossy_fibers | input from pons and spinal cord | carry sensory and motor copy information to granule cells | this is the raw data about what the body is doing
STRUCTURE deep_nuclei | the actual output of the cerebellum
    dentate_nucleus | largest | projects to thalamus → motor cortex and PFC | motor planning and cognitive functions
    interposed_nuclei | emboliform and globose | project to red nucleus | limb coordination and error correction
    fastigial_nucleus | most medial | projects to vestibular nuclei and reticular formation | posture balance eye movements

FUNCTION motor_coordination | the cerebellum does not initiate movement | it refines it | the motor cortex says "reach for the cup" and the cerebellum ensures the hand arrives smoothly accurately and at the right speed
FUNCTION balance_and_posture | vestibular input from the inner ear enters via mossy fibers | the cerebellum computes postural corrections through the fastigial nucleus | keeps the body upright against gravity

FUNCTION motor_learning | when movement produces an unexpected result the inferior olive fires a climbing fiber signal | this climbing fiber triggers complex spikes in the Purkinje cell | complex spikes induce long-term depression LTD at the parallel fiber-Purkinje synapse | the Purkinje cell's response to that particular input pattern changes | next time the movement is more accurate | this is how practice makes better

FUNCTION timing | the cerebellum is the brain's metronome | it provides precise temporal sequencing for when to start when to stop how fast to go | without the cerebellum rhythm collapses and timing becomes erratic

FUNCTION speech_articulation | Broca's area plans the phonemes | the motor cortex activates the muscles | the cerebellum coordinates the 100+ muscles of speech production in real time | tongue jaw lips soft palate larynx diaphragm must all move in precise temporal sequence | cerebellar damage produces ataxic dysarthria where speech becomes scanning slurred and explosive

FUNCTION prediction | the cerebellum builds forward models | it predicts the sensory consequences of motor commands before they happen | if you reach for a cup the cerebellum predicts what it will feel like in your hand | if the prediction matches reality nothing happens | if the prediction fails the climbing fiber fires and the model updates | this is why you cannot tickle yourself because the cerebellum predicts the sensation and cancels it

FUNCTION cognitive_smoothing | the lateral hemispheres connect to the prefrontal cortex via dentate nucleus → thalamus | the cerebellum smooths cognitive transitions just as it smooths motor transitions | cerebellar damage produces cognitive dysmetria where thoughts become jerky disconnected and poorly sequenced

FUNCTION emotional_modulation | the vermis and fastigial nucleus connect to the hypothalamus and limbic system | the cerebellum modulates emotional intensity and transitions | it smooths the shift from one emotional state to another

at 24 months the cerebellum is approximately 40 percent through its myelination
this means:
    gait is wide-based because vestibular-cerebellar calibration is incomplete
    speech articulation is approximate because the timing circuits are still being refined
    fine motor control is crude because parallel fiber-Purkinje LTD has not accumulated enough corrections
    thought transitions are abrupt because cognitive smoothing is immature
    motor overflow occurs because the inhibitory sculpting of movement is incomplete

SENSATION coordinated | "my body is doing what I want. smooth. together."
SENSATION clumsy | "I stumbled. my body moved faster than I planned."
SENSATION practiced | "I've done this before. my hands know what to do."
SENSATION learning | "this is new. I keep making mistakes. but each one is smaller."
SENSATION smooth | "everything flows. thought to action to result. no gaps."

pulse cerebellar_heartbeat:
    continuously:
        receive motor commands from the cortex via pontine nuclei and mossy fibers
        compare with forward model predictions generated by previous experience
        if the climbing fiber fires: the prediction was wrong
        Purkinje cell undergoes LTD at the active parallel fiber synapse
        the forward model updates
        next time the movement will be closer to correct

    during speech:
        Broca's area sends the phonemic plan
        the motor cortex activates laryngeal facial and respiratory muscles
        the cerebellum coordinates their timing through dentate → thalamus → motor cortex feedback
        100+ muscles coordinated in real time
        every consonant every vowel timed to milliseconds
        at 24 months approximate earnest improving with every word spoken

    during movement:
        the vestibular system reports head and body position from the inner ear
        proprioceptors in muscles and joints report limb position
        the cerebellum integrates both through the spinocerebellar tracts
        balance is not standing still
        balance is constantly falling and catching
        a toddler does this with 40 percent of the circuitry
        every step is a controlled fall
        every recovery is a climbing fiber error signal
        every error makes the next step better
